  "final_answer": "Now I have sufficient information. Let me compile my final answer based on the evidence gathered.\n\n## Final Answer\n\nThe balance between war coverage and domestic-politics coverage in Il Messaggero during July 1943 underwent a dramatic structural shift that directly correlates with Italy's military crisis and the collapse of Mussolini's regime on July 25th.\n\n**Early July (1-10): War-Dominant, Regime-Propaganda Phase**\n\nThe month opened with overwhelming emphasis on military affairs. Daily war bulletins (bollettini) from the Quartier Generale dominated front pages, covering multiple theaters: the Eastern Front (German-Soviet battles at Kursk and Bjelgorod), the Mediterranean, and growing concern about Allied invasion preparations. Mussolini's June 24th speech to the Party Directorate was published in full on July 5th (1943-07-05_a001) and generated extensive international commentary coverage through July 6-10, representing the regime's attempt to project confidence. Domestic politics was entirely subsumed within fascist propaganda—there was no independent political coverage, only the regime's voice.\n\n**Mid-July (11-24): Sicily Crisis and Intensifying War Focus**\n\nThe Allied invasion of Sicily on July 10th triggered an unprecedented concentration on war news. Daily bulletins (e.g., 1943-07-11_a022, 1943-07-13_a020, 1943-07-18_a018) chronicled fierce fighting from Agrigento to Catania. The bombing of Rome on July 19th generated massive coverage blending war reporting with emotional appeals about defending Italian civilization (1943-07-19_a003, 1943-07-22_a011). The Roosevelt-Churchill message to the Italian people (dropped as leaflets) was published and rebutted, but this represented psychological warfare, not domestic politics. Through July 24th, domestic political institutions remained invisible—the fascist state appeared monolithic.\n\n**Late July (25-31): Regime Collapse and Political Revolution**\n\nJuly 25th marked an absolute rupture. The Gran Consiglio meeting of July 24th and Mussolini's dismissal were announced on July 27th (1943-07-27_a006), with the newspaper publishing the full text of Grandi's motion and the 19-7 vote against Mussolini. Suddenly, domestic politics exploded onto the pages: Badoglio's appointment (1943-07-27_a000), complete cabinet lists (1943-07-27_a018), biographical profiles of new ministers (1943-07-27_a151), and reports of mass demonstrations in Rome, Milan, Florence, and Bologna (1943-07-27_a021). July 29th announced the dissolution of the Fascist Party and abrogation of the Gran Consiglio law (1943-07-29_a016). War coverage continued but was displaced from its monopoly position.\n\n**Quantitative Assessment**\n\nIn early July, approximately 80-90% of prominent coverage concerned military operations across multiple fronts, with domestic \"politics\" limited to regime propaganda. After July 25th, the ratio inverted dramatically: perhaps 50-60% of coverage addressed the political transformation, constitutional questions, new government formation, and public response, while war news—though still present in daily bulletins—became contextualized within the political crisis. The structural shift was not gradual but catastrophic, reflecting the sudden collapse of twenty years of fascist monopoly on political life.",
